insert into public.questions
  (id, parent_id, type, category, subtopic, importance, difficulty, candidate_level, region, question, key_points, model_answer)
values
(1812, NULL, 'primary', $x$Behavioral / Fit$x$, $x$Wrong Against Manager$x$, 'standard', 2, 'intern', 'Global', $x$Tell me about a time you pushed back on a manager or team lead because you were convinced they were wrong - and it turned out THEY were right and you were wrong. How did you realize it, and what did you do once you knew?$x$, $x$["Specific disagreement and stakes", "Real conviction then genuine error", "Trigger that revealed being wrong", "Owns it fast with no excuses", "Communicates the reversal to the manager", "Updates view of their judgment", "Humility without self-flagellation"]$x$::jsonb, $x$On a student consulting project, our team lead wanted to scrap a survey approach I had built and just use interviews. I argued hard that the survey gave us statistical weight and pushed to keep both. She let me run it. The response rate came back at under fifteen percent, totally unrepresentative, and the interviews she favored surfaced the real insight that drove our final recommendation. The moment the data came in, I could see she had read the situation better than I had - she knew our sample was too small and too biased to mean anything. I went to her directly, told her she had been right and I had been wrong to dig in, and we reallocated my time to the interview synthesis. What I took from it is that conviction is not evidence, and seniority often reflects pattern recognition I do not have yet. Now when I disagree I still say so once, clearly, but I hold it more loosely and I watch for the early signal that I am the one missing something rather than waiting to be proven wrong.$x$),
(1813, NULL, 'primary', $x$Behavioral / Fit$x$, $x$Cut Corner Pressure$x$, 'standard', 3, 'intern', 'Global', $x$Describe a time you felt pressure - from a deadline, a teammate, or your own workload - to cut a corner on accuracy or to present something as more finished than it really was. What did you actually do?$x$, $x$["Concrete temptation named", "Source of pressure identified", "Chose integrity over speed", "Flagged the limitation explicitly", "Quantifies the risk of the shortcut", "Practical mitigation not just refusal", "Reputation and trust reasoning"]$x$::jsonb, $x$I was the analyst on a student-run fund pitch and we were an hour from presenting when I found I had not actually reconciled the comps - I had pulled multiples from a screener but not checked the calendarization or the share counts. The easy move was to present the numbers as solid because nobody on the panel would catch it that day. I did not. I told our team captain the comps were unverified and could be off enough to change the valuation conclusion, so we should caveat them rather than lead with them. We flagged the range as preliminary in the deck and I cleaned the data overnight before the written submission. It cost me some sleep and a little pride in the moment, but presenting an unchecked number as a finished one is exactly the kind of thing that destroys trust the first time someone catches it. I would rather be the person who says this part is not done yet than the person whose work has to be re-checked every time.$x$),
(1814, NULL, 'primary', $x$Behavioral / Fit$x$, $x$Unresolved Peer Conflict$x$, 'standard', 2, 'intern', 'Global', $x$Tell me about a conflict with a peer that you were NOT able to resolve - it ended unsatisfyingly. Looking back, what would you do differently, and what did you actually learn from not fixing it?$x$, $x$["Honest about the unresolved outcome", "No villain framing of the peer", "Specific failed attempts to fix it", "Real self-critique not deflection", "Concrete different approach", "Lesson that changed later behavior", "Maturity over a tidy ending"]$x$::jsonb, $x$On a group thesis, a teammate and I clashed over scope - I wanted depth on two companies, he wanted a broad sweep of ten, and neither of us moved. I tried compromising on the page count and I tried appealing to the brief, but I never actually sat down and asked what was driving him, which I later realized was that he was overloaded in another class and wanted something faster to finish. We split the work awkwardly, the final piece felt stitched together, and the relationship stayed cool. What I would do differently is treat it as a problem to understand before a position to win - I argued my preference repeatedly instead of getting curious about his constraint. The lesson stuck: most peer conflicts I have seen are really about an unspoken pressure, not the thing being argued about. Since then I open with what is going on for you on this, and even when we still disagree, knowing the real constraint usually lets us find something workable. That one did not, and I own my half of why.$x$),
(1815, NULL, 'primary', $x$Behavioral / Fit$x$, $x$Public Mistake Recovery$x$, 'advanced', 3, 'analyst', 'Global', $x$Tell me about a mistake of yours that was visible to people beyond your immediate team - a senior banker, a client, or a wide distribution. Walk me through the hour after you realized, and how you rebuilt credibility afterward.$x$, $x$["Genuinely visible high-stakes error", "Immediate escalation not concealment", "Owns it without over-apologizing", "Concrete correction and comms", "Root-cause process fix", "Credibility rebuilt over time", "Calm under exposure"]$x$::jsonb, $x$I sent an updated operating model to a client distribution list with a broken link in one revenue driver, so a sensitivity table showed numbers that were off by a meaningful margin, and an MD spotted it in front of the client on a call. The hour after was the test. I did not go quiet or hope it slid by - I immediately messaged the MD that the table was wrong, told him the corrected figures, and asked him to let me send a clean version with a short note rather than him patching it live. We sent a corrected file within forty minutes with a one-line acknowledgment, no long grovel. Then I built a check tab that flagged any hardcode or broken reference before anything left my hands, and I started having a second analyst eyeball client-facing outputs. Rebuilding credibility was not the apology - it was that the next ten things I sent were clean, so the MD stopped re-checking my work. People forgive a visible error fast if you own it instantly and never repeat the category.$x$),
(1816, NULL, 'primary', $x$Behavioral / Fit$x$, $x$Hard Feedback To Peer$x$, 'advanced', 3, 'analyst', 'Global', $x$Tell me about a time you had to give difficult feedback to a peer - someone at your own level, with no authority over them. What did you say, how did they take it, and did anything actually change?$x$, $x$["Peer not subordinate dynamic", "Specific behavior not character", "Private direct timely delivery", "Acknowledges the discomfort honestly", "Their reaction handled well", "Measurable change or honest outcome", "Preserved the relationship"]$x$::jsonb, $x$A fellow analyst on my team kept committing to turnaround times in front of the VP and then quietly leaning on the rest of us to hit them, which was burning the staffing pool. No authority, just a peer, so I could not order anything. I pulled him aside privately, kept it to the behavior rather than calling him a credibility-grabber, and said something like - when you commit us to a midnight turn without checking, I end up reshuffling my night and it is starting to cost me. He got a bit defensive at first and said he was just trying to look responsive. I acknowledged that the instinct was right but the method was offloading the cost onto people who had not agreed. What changed was real - he started pinging the team before committing, even a quick can we hit this. It was uncomfortable because we were friendly and equal, but I would rather have one awkward five-minute conversation than let resentment build silently and poison the team.$x$),
(1817, NULL, 'primary', $x$Behavioral / Fit$x$, $x$Owning Team Failure$x$, 'advanced', 3, 'analyst', 'Global', $x$Tell me about a team or deal outcome that failed where the fault was genuinely shared - not solely yours. How did you handle accountability when you could easily have pointed at someone else?$x$, $x$["Shared not solely-own fault", "Resists the blame-shifting temptation", "Owns a specific personal share", "Avoids throwing teammates under the bus", "Distinguishes accountability from blame", "Forward-looking process fix", "Leadership instinct at junior level"]$x$::jsonb, $x$We lost a pitch partly because the comps universe was off and partly because the senior narrative did not land - the data issue was shared between me and another analyst, and the framing was above my pay grade. In the post-mortem it would have been easy to say the bad slide was not my section. Instead I said the part I owned: I had assumed the other analyst was screening for the same size cutoff I was, and I never confirmed it, so a couple of misfit comps got through on my watch too. I did not name him or point upward at the narrative - that helps nobody and the VP can see the deck. The distinction I try to hold is that blame is about who pays and accountability is about who fixes it, and I would rather be known as the person who steps toward the failure than away from it. Concretely we agreed on a single owner for the comps universe going forward with a documented screen, so the seam I had fallen into could not happen again. Owning my slice without scapegoating is what kept the team functional afterward.$x$),
(1818, NULL, 'primary', $x$Behavioral / Fit$x$, $x$Ethical Line Client$x$, 'advanced', 3, 'associate', 'Global', $x$Describe an ethical dilemma where the technically permissible thing and the right thing came apart - for example pressure to present an analysis in a way that was defensible but misleading to a client. How did you handle it, and what did it cost you?$x$, $x$["True dilemma not an easy call", "Legal-but-misleading distinction", "Names the pressure source", "Held the line constructively", "Offered an honest alternative framing", "Acknowledges the real cost", "Long-term trust over short win"]$x$::jsonb, $x$On a sell-side process I was asked to present a management projection set as the base case in our materials when I genuinely believed it was aggressive - the hockey-stick was technically the client's own plan, so showing it was defensible, but leading with it without context would have steered a buyer in a way I thought was misleading. The pressure came from wanting the asset to show well. I did not refuse to show management's numbers - that was their plan and they were entitled to it. What I pushed for was honesty in the framing: present management case alongside a clearly labeled sensitized case and let the range speak, rather than anchoring everyone on the optimistic line. It created friction with a senior banker who felt I was diluting the story, and for a day or two I was the person slowing things down. But the right buyer was going to sensitize those numbers anyway, and getting caught dressing up a forecast costs you the relationship and the next mandate. Defensible is the floor, not the standard. We ran it with both cases and the process held up under diligence.$x$),
(1819, NULL, 'primary', $x$Behavioral / Fit$x$, $x$Principle Against Room$x$, 'advanced', 3, 'associate', 'Global', $x$Tell me about a time you held a position on principle when the entire room - including people senior to you - was leaning the other way. How did you make the case without grandstanding, and were you ultimately right?$x$, $x$["Genuine lone-dissent situation", "Substantive principle not ego", "Made the case calmly with evidence", "Knew when to stop pushing", "Honest on whether vindicated", "Disagree-and-commit maturity", "Read of senior dynamics"]$x$::jsonb, $x$In a deal-team discussion the room was coalescing around recommending the higher headline bid for a client, and I was the one arguing the lower bid was actually better because the certainty of close was much higher - the top bidder had a financing contingency and a shaky track record. Everyone senior was anchored on the number. I did not make it a stand or repeat myself loudly. I laid it out once with the specifics: here is the financing gap, here is their record of re-trading, here is what a broken deal costs the client versus the spread between the bids. I asked the question rather than declaring the answer - what happens to the client if the top bid falls apart in month three. Then I stopped, because past a point repeating yourself is ego, not advocacy. The MD ultimately weighted certainty more heavily in how we framed it to the client, and the lower-risk bidder is the one that closed cleanly. I was right that time, but the part I am actually proud of is making the case on the merits once and then being willing to commit either way.$x$),
(1820, NULL, 'primary', $x$Behavioral / Fit$x$, $x$Influence Without Authority$x$, 'standard', 2, 'intern', 'Global', $x$Tell me about a time you needed a peer or someone on another team to do something for you, but you had no authority to make them. They were busy and it was not their priority. How did you actually get them to say yes?$x$, $x$["Specific situation with no formal authority", "Understood the other person's incentives or constraints", "Framed the ask around their interests not just yours", "Made it low-friction to say yes, a concrete specific favor", "Built credibility or traded value, reciprocity", "Clear outcome, they delivered", "Honest reflection on relationship maintained"]$x$::jsonb, $x$Last year I ran the finance section of a student-run consulting project and needed our data lead, who was on another team, to pull a clean dataset for me by Friday. I had zero authority over him and he was slammed with his own deliverable. So instead of just pinging him with a demand, I went to him in person, asked what was on his plate, and realized his blocker was that nobody had specced exactly what columns they needed. I did that work for him - I wrote a one-page spec with the exact fields and format so the pull would take him twenty minutes instead of two hours of guessing. I also offered to proofread his section in return. He got it to me a day early. The lesson I took is that influence without authority is mostly about removing friction and making your ask the easiest thing on their list, plus showing you are willing to give something back rather than just take. I have leaned on that ever since whenever I need something from someone who does not report to me.$x$),
(1821, NULL, 'primary', $x$Behavioral / Fit$x$, $x$Leading Peers No Title$x$, 'standard', 2, 'intern', 'Global', $x$Describe a time you ended up effectively leading a group of your own peers when nobody had been put formally in charge. How did you take the lead without a title, and how did you keep people bought in rather than resentful?$x$, $x$["Group with no formal leader, a vacuum", "Stepped up through action not self-appointment", "Earned authority by doing the unglamorous coordinating work", "Gave others ownership, credit and voice", "Handled a peer who pushed back", "Concrete result delivered on time", "Awareness of resentment risk and how it was managed"]$x$::jsonb, $x$In my final-year group project we had five people and no assigned leader, and two weeks in we were drifting with no plan. I did not announce I was taking over, because that gets resented fast with peers. Instead I just started doing the connective work nobody wanted - I set up a shared tracker, sent a short agenda before each meeting, and summarized who owned what afterward. People gravitated to that because it made their lives easier. The thing I was careful about was not hoarding the interesting parts. I let others pick the sections they were excited about and I made a point of crediting their work out loud when we presented. One teammate initially bristled and felt I was steering too much, so I asked him to run the next meeting himself, which defused it and actually got him more invested. We finished early and got the top mark. What I learned is that leading peers is earned by carrying load and sharing credit, not by claiming the role.$x$),
(1822, NULL, 'primary', $x$Behavioral / Fit$x$, $x$Navigating Ambiguity$x$, 'advanced', 3, 'analyst', 'Global', $x$Tell me about a time you were handed a problem where there was genuinely no clearly right answer and the path was completely undefined. How did you create structure out of the ambiguity, and how did you decide when you had done enough?$x$, $x$["Genuinely open-ended problem, no template", "Broke ambiguity into smaller answerable questions", "Made defensible assumptions and stated them", "Sought input or precedent to narrow the space", "Picked a direction and committed despite uncertainty", "Defined what good enough looked like, time-boxed it", "Outcome and what they would refine"]$x$::jsonb, $x$On a deal early in my analyst year an MD asked me to size a market for a target operating in a niche where there were no clean comps and no off-the-shelf data. There was no right answer and no template, which was paralyzing at first. So I broke it into pieces I could actually answer - I built it bottom-up from customer counts and average spend, then cross-checked it top-down from industry revenue, and where I had to assume something I wrote the assumption down explicitly so it could be challenged. I also called a colleague who had covered an adjacent sector to sanity-check my ranges rather than reinvent everything. The hard part was knowing when to stop, because you can refine an estimate forever. I time-boxed it - I decided that once my two methods landed within a reasonable band and the assumptions were transparent, that was good enough to bring to the MD with a range rather than a false-precision single number. He pushed on two assumptions, we adjusted, and it held up. I learned ambiguity is manageable if you make the unknowns explicit and commit to a defensible range.$x$),
(1823, NULL, 'primary', $x$Behavioral / Fit$x$, $x$Explaining To Non-Technical Audience$x$, 'advanced', 3, 'analyst', 'Global', $x$Tell me about a time you had to get a technical or financial point across to an audience that did not share your expertise. How did you read that they were not following, and what did you change to actually land it?$x$, $x$["Audience genuinely lacked the technical background", "Picked up the signal that they were lost", "Stripped jargon, reframed in terms the audience knew", "Used analogy, led with the answer not the mechanics", "Checked for understanding rather than plowing ahead", "Concrete outcome, the audience got comfortable or acted", "Reflection that clarity is part of the job not dumbing-down"]$x$::jsonb, $x$On a sell-side process I had to walk the founders of the target through our valuation, and they had built a great company but had no finance background. My first instinct was to present the DCF and the trading comps the way I would internally, but I could see in the early call that the WACC and EBITDA-multiple language was losing them, and a client who does not follow the logic cannot get comfortable with the number. So I reset. I dropped the jargon and reframed it around things they lived every day - I tied the valuation back to their own revenue growth and margins, used a simple analogy for why future cash flows get discounted, and led with the range and what drove it rather than the mechanics. I also paused often to check they were with me instead of plowing through slides. By the end they were the ones poking at the assumptions, which is exactly what I wanted. The deal got done at a number they understood and believed. What I took from it is that technical work only creates value if the audience can actually absorb it, so reading who is in the room and adjusting the level is part of the job, not a dumbing-down.$x$),
(1824, NULL, 'primary', $x$Behavioral / Fit$x$, $x$Delegating When Overloaded$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'associate', 'Global', $x$Tell me about a time you were genuinely overloaded and had to delegate work you would normally have done yourself. How did you decide what to hand off versus keep, and what did you do when the work came back not quite right?$x$, $x$["Real capacity ceiling forced delegation", "Triaged what to keep versus hand off by risk and skill", "Delegated with clear context and expectations, not just a dump", "Resisted the urge to do it all themselves", "Handled imperfect output by coaching not silently redoing", "Outcome, the deliverable still landed", "Reflection on trust and developing the team"]$x$::jsonb, $x$During a stretch where I had two live deals colliding I physically could not do everything myself, and the instinct as an associate is to just grind it all, which does not scale. I had to triage. I kept the things that were high-stakes or required judgment only I had - the client-facing materials and the parts of the model with tricky assumptions - and I handed the analyst the comps build and the formatting-heavy appendix. The key was that I did not just dump it; I gave him the context, told him what the output needed to look like, and pointed him to a prior precedent. When the comps came back with a couple of wrong screening criteria, I did not silently fix it at 2am, because that teaches nothing. I walked him through what was off and why it mattered, then had him redo it, which took longer that night but meant he owned it cleanly the next time. Both deals' materials went out on time. What I learned is delegation is a multiplier only if you invest in context and treat mistakes as coaching, not as proof you should have done it yourself.$x$),
(1825, NULL, 'primary', $x$Behavioral / Fit$x$, $x$Mentoring A Struggler$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'associate', 'Global', $x$Tell me about a time you supported someone on your team who was genuinely struggling - falling behind or losing confidence. How did you diagnose what was actually wrong, and what specifically did you do that helped?$x$, $x$["Recognized someone struggling early, read the signals", "Diagnosed root cause, skill versus confidence versus overload", "Approached privately and without judgment", "Specific concrete intervention not vague encouragement", "Balanced support with maintaining the bar", "Measurable improvement or honest outcome", "What they would do differently next time"]$x$::jsonb, $x$I had a junior analyst on a deal who started missing details and going quiet in meetings, which was unlike him. Rather than just flag the errors, I pulled him aside one-on-one to figure out what was actually going on, because the symptom is rarely the cause. It turned out he was not short on ability - he was drowning across three workstreams and had stopped asking questions because he felt he should already know the answers, so small confusions were compounding into mistakes. So I did a few concrete things. I helped him sequence his work so he was not context-switching every hour, I set up a quick fifteen-minute check-in each morning so he had a low-stakes place to surface questions, and I deliberately answered his early ones without any hint of judgment so it felt safe to ask. I was careful not to lower the bar - the work still had to be right - but I made the path to right more supported. Within two weeks his error rate dropped and he was speaking up again. The lesson was that struggling is usually a process or confidence problem, not a capability one, and diagnosing that before reacting is what actually helps.$x$),
(1826, NULL, 'primary', $x$Behavioral / Fit$x$, $x$Integrity Under Pressure$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'associate', 'Global', $x$Tell me about a time you spotted something in your own team's work that was technically misleading or did not tie out, but correcting it would have weakened a story people wanted to tell. What did you do?$x$, $x$["Identified a real integrity issue, a soft or misleading number", "Acknowledged the pull to stay quiet and let it ride", "Raised it rather than burying it, to the right person", "Proposed a concrete fix, adjust or disclose clearly", "Weighed short-term optic against long-term credibility", "Outcome, corrected and the work still stood honestly", "Reflection that trust and credibility are the product"]$x$::jsonb, $x$On a pitch the team was assembling a valuation and one of my comparable companies had a data point that made our target look meaningfully cheaper, which the deal team liked because it supported a higher price story. When I dug in, that comp had just closed a large acquisition, so its multiple was distorted and not really apples-to-apples. The easy thing was to stay quiet and let a flattering number ride. Instead I flagged it to my VP before the book went out, showed why the multiple was misleading, and proposed either adjusting it or footnoting the distortion clearly. It was uncomfortable because it weakened the headline, but putting a number in front of a client that I knew was not clean is not something I was willing to do - our credibility is the product. We corrected it and the revised range still supported the pitch, just honestly. The MD actually thanked me later because getting challenged by the client on a soft comp would have been far worse. The lesson I hold is that the moment you let a number you do not believe go out the door, you have traded long-term trust for a short-term optic, and that trade is never worth it.$x$),
(1827, NULL, 'primary', $x$Behavioral / Fit$x$, $x$Giving A Peer Hard Feedback$x$, 'advanced', 3, 'analyst', 'Global', $x$Tell me about a time a peer's work was falling short in a way that was affecting you or the team, and you decided to give them the hard feedback directly rather than escalate or absorb it. How did you raise it without damaging the relationship?$x$, $x$["Peer's shortfall was real and had a tangible cost", "Chose to address directly instead of escalating or stewing", "Picked the moment and framed it around the work not the person", "Assumed a fixable cause, diagnosed before judging", "Paired the criticism with something concrete and actionable", "Outcome, behavior improved and friction eased", "Reflection on how to deliver peer feedback well"]$x$::jsonb, $x$On a deal I was sharing a workstream with another analyst whose sections kept coming in late and with formatting and tie-out errors, and it was landing on me to clean up at midnight, which was quietly building resentment. Rather than escalate to the associate or stew, I decided to talk to him directly first. I picked a calm moment, not a crunch, and framed it around the shared deliverable rather than attacking him - I said the back-and-forth on his pages was costing us both time and asked whether something was getting in the way. It turned out he had never been shown the team's formatting conventions and was guessing. So instead of just criticizing, I walked him through a clean precedent and we agreed he would self-check tie-outs before sending. I was honest that the lateness was a problem, but I gave him a concrete path to fix it. His pages got noticeably tighter within a week and the friction went away. What I learned is that giving a peer hard feedback works when you make it about the work, assume a fixable cause rather than bad intent, and pair the criticism with something actionable.$x$),
(1828, NULL, 'primary', $x$Behavioral / Fit$x$, $x$Error Before Client$x$, 'standard', 2, 'intern', 'Global', $x$You are an intern. Ten minutes before a deck goes to the client, you spot a number in the valuation summary that you are fairly sure is wrong, but you are not certain. The associate who built it has stepped out and the VP is on a call. Walk me through exactly what you do.$x$, $x$["Speed Plus Accuracy", "Quickly Verify The Suspected Error", "Trace To Source Not Guess", "Escalate Immediately Despite Junior Status", "Flag To VP Even If Mid-Call", "Frame As Question Not Accusation", "Better Awkward Than Wrong To Client"]$x$::jsonb, $x$First I would not sit on it - ten minutes is enough to act but not to agonize, so I move fast. I would pull up the underlying model and trace the number to its source to confirm whether it is actually wrong, because flagging a phantom error wastes everyone's time. If I confirm it or I am still genuinely unsure, I escalate immediately rather than quietly fixing it myself, since a junior changing a client-facing figure unilaterally is risky. The associate is out, so I would interrupt the VP - a quiet note, a text, or stepping in to say I think the EV/EBITDA on the summary page may be off and here is why. I would frame it as a question, not an accusation, and have the specific cell and the corrected figure ready so they can decide in seconds. The instinct to protect the senior from looking bad by staying silent is exactly the wrong one here. A slightly awkward interruption is far cheaper than a wrong number reaching the client, and seniors remember the junior who caught it, not the one who noticed and froze.$x$),
(1829, NULL, 'primary', $x$Behavioral / Fit$x$, $x$Managing Up Churn$x$, 'advanced', 3, 'analyst', 'Global', $x$A VP keeps sending a deliverable back to you round after round, late into the night, but the changes have stopped being substantive - reversing earlier edits, cosmetic tweaks that will not change how the client reads it. At what point, if any, do you push back, and how?$x$, $x$["Early Iteration Is The Job Not Churn", "Distinguish Substance From Cosmetic Rework", "Watch For Signal Edits Reverse Or Add No Value", "Push Back Only Once Pattern Is Clear", "Frame As Protecting Time And Quality", "Suggest Locking Version Or Checking With MD", "Comply Without Complaint If Overruled"]$x$::jsonb, $x$I would not push back on the first or second round - early iteration is the job, and a VP refining a live deliverable usually has a reason I cannot see, like where the MD wants the story to land. So I execute the rounds cleanly and fast. What I watch for is the signal that we have crossed from substance into churn: changes that reverse earlier ones, formatting tweaks at 2am with no analytical change, or edits that will not move how the client reads the page. Once I see that pattern and the deliverable is not due for a while, I would gently surface it rather than silently absorb infinite turns. I might ask whether it is worth locking the current version and walking the MD through it before we polish further, so we are not perfecting a page the MD may redirect anyway. I frame it as protecting their time and the deck quality, never as me being tired. If they want more rounds regardless, I do them without complaint - but I have at least given the VP a clean offramp and shown I am thinking about where the real value is, not just taking orders.$x$),
(1830, NULL, 'primary', $x$Behavioral / Fit$x$, $x$Double-Staffed Deadline$x$, 'advanced', 3, 'analyst', 'Global', $x$You are double-staffed on two live deals and it becomes clear around midnight that you physically cannot finish both deliverables by their morning deadlines - one will slip. How do you handle that moment?$x$, $x$["Recognize And Flag Early Not At Deadline", "Communicate Before The Miss", "Assess Which Deliverable Is Truly Time-Critical", "Bring A Proposed Plan Not Just A Problem", "Ask Seniors To Re-Prioritize Or Add Resource", "Offer Partial Or Interim Deliverable", "Protect Both Relationships Honestly"]$x$::jsonb, $x$The worst version of this is going silent and letting one deadline blow at 8am with no warning - seniors can absorb a slip, but not a surprise. So the moment I am confident the math does not work, around midnight, I communicate rather than grinding in hope. Before I ping anyone I do the triage myself: which deliverable is genuinely time-critical - is one going to a client meeting at nine and the other an internal review that can flex? I figure out what I actually believe should give. Then I go to both staffers, or the more senior one, with a proposed plan, not just a problem: here is where each stands, here is what I can realistically finish well by morning, and here is the one I would push to noon - do you agree, or can we pull in another analyst for an hour. I would also offer an interim version, like a clean draft with two pages still rough, so nothing arrives as a blank. The skill is owning the prioritization call but giving seniors the chance to overrule it, and being honest early enough that both teams keep trusting me.$x$),
(1831, NULL, 'primary', $x$Behavioral / Fit$x$, $x$Disagreeing With Thesis$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'associate', 'Global', $x$As an associate, you come to genuinely disagree with the core thesis the team is pitching - say you think the synergy assumptions underpinning the whole strategic rationale are unrealistic - but you are the junior voice in the room. How do you handle that, and where is the line on how hard you push?$x$, $x$["Distinguish Disagreement From Insubordination", "Pressure-Test With Evidence Not Just Opinion", "Raise Privately With Deal Lead First", "Frame As Risk To Client Credibility", "Know When To Disagree And Commit", "Escalation Has Limits Below Career-Risk", "Document Concern If Truly Material"]$x$::jsonb, $x$I would separate having a contrarian view from being insubordinate - the job is to make the team's product better, not to win an argument. First I make sure my disagreement is rigorous: I build the case quantitatively, stress the synergy numbers, benchmark them against comparable deals, and see whether they survive scrutiny, because opinion without evidence carries no weight as the junior voice. Then I raise it privately with the deal lead before any group setting, framed around client risk not ego: if the client's own diligence cracks these synergies, our credibility and the whole rationale go with it. I would offer a more defensible range rather than just saying I dislike it. After that it is genuinely their call. If they hear me and still proceed, on most issues I disagree and commit - I have flagged it, the decision sits above me, and I execute fully. The line is that I push hard with facts up to the point of a real fiduciary or ethical problem; short of that I do not torch the deal or go around the lead. If it is truly material, I might put my concern in a short note so it is on record, then get behind the team.$x$),
(1832, NULL, 'primary', $x$Behavioral / Fit$x$, $x$Five To Ten Years$x$, 'standard', 2, 'intern', 'Global', $x$Forget the three-year answer. Where do you genuinely see yourself in five to ten years, and be honest about whether that picture even includes banking?$x$, $x$["Specific directional vision not vague", "Honesty about banking vs exit", "Skills banking builds toward goal", "Optionality acknowledged not scripted", "Internally consistent with why-IB", "Self-aware about uncertainty"]$x$::jsonb, $x$I will be honest that a ten-year picture is a direction, not a fixed point. In five years I want to be a strong associate or early VP who can run a deal process end to end, own client relationships, and mentor juniors well. Beyond that, ten years out, I see two credible paths and I am open about both. One is staying in banking and building a sector franchise where I genuinely know the buyers, the sellers, and the strategic logic in a space like industrials or healthcare. The other is moving to the principal side, a fund or a corporate development seat, where I use the same analytical and relationship muscles to actually own outcomes rather than advise on them. What ties those together is the foundation banking builds, modeling rigor, judgment under pressure, and reading what a client really needs. I would rather show you I have thought seriously about the trade-offs than recite a path I cannot defend. Either way, the next few years here are the part I am sure about.$x$),
(1833, NULL, 'primary', $x$Behavioral / Fit$x$, $x$Managers Growth Note$x$, 'standard', 2, 'intern', 'Global', $x$If I called your last manager right now and asked the single biggest area they would want you to improve, what would they say, and do you agree with it?$x$, $x$["Names specific real improvement area", "Frames from managers perspective", "Evidence it is genuine not humblebrag", "Agreement or honest pushback", "Concrete steps already taken", "Shows coachability and self-awareness"]$x$::jsonb, $x$My last manager would say I sometimes try to perfect a deliverable before checking in, so I over-invest in something that then needs to change direction. She told me directly after I spent most of a day polishing an analysis she only wanted as a rough cut. And I agree with her, it was a real pattern, not a one-off. What was happening underneath was that I treated asking for an early gut-check as a sign I was not capable, when actually it is the opposite. So I changed how I work. Now when I get an ambiguous task I send back the structure and a couple of assumptions within the first hour, before I build anything heavy, and I confirm the level of polish needed up front. The result is I waste far less time and the senior gets to steer early when steering is cheap. I would rather you hear the honest version than a weakness dressed up as a strength, because the point is I caught it and fixed how I operate.$x$),
(1834, NULL, 'primary', $x$Behavioral / Fit$x$, $x$Sustainable Stress$x$, 'standard', 2, 'any', 'Global', $x$Tell me about a time you noticed your own stress or fatigue starting to affect your work. What were the warning signs, and what did you actually do about it?$x$, $x$["Specific moment with real warning signs", "Self-awareness it was affecting output", "Named limits or asked for help early", "Concrete action not just pushing harder", "Protected recovery sleep or reset deliberately", "Failure mode is hiding strain not feeling it"]$x$::jsonb, $x$There was a stretch during my last internship where I quietly hit a wall, two big workstreams collided with finals, and I noticed I was rereading the same email three times and snapping at small things. The honest part is I almost said nothing, because I assumed admitting it meant I could not handle the role. What I actually did was different. I flagged to my staffer that I was at capacity and asked, concretely, which of the two deliverables was the real priority for the next forty-eight hours, rather than pretending I could do both perfectly. He resequenced one of them, and the work that mattered most got my best effort instead of both getting a tired version. Separately I forced myself back to basics, a hard sleep floor and a thirty-minute run, because those are the first things I drop and the first things that break me. What I learned is that the failure mode is not feeling the strain, everyone does. It is hiding it until the work suffers. Now I treat naming my limits early as part of the job, not a confession.$x$),
(1835, NULL, 'primary', $x$Behavioral / Fit$x$, $x$Teach In Two Minutes$x$, 'advanced', 3, 'associate', 'Global', $x$Curveball. Teach me something you know genuinely well, anything at all, in two minutes, as if I am smart but know nothing about it.$x$, $x$["Picks topic of real depth", "Structures from first principles", "Defines jargon before using it", "Concrete example or analogy", "Reads the listener checks understanding", "Confident clear communication under spotlight"]$x$::jsonb, $x$Let me teach you the basic idea behind how bicycle gears work, because it is a clean example of a useful concept. The core principle is a trade-off between force and distance, and you cannot beat it, you can only choose where to sit on it. A bicycle has two sets of toothed rings, one at the pedals and one at the rear wheel, connected by a chain. When you pick a gear, you are really choosing the ratio between how many teeth are up front versus at the back. A high gear means one turn of the pedals drives the wheel many turns, which is fast but takes a lot of force, so it is great on flat ground and miserable uphill. A low gear is the reverse, the pedals spin a lot for little wheel movement, so it feels easy and lets you climb a steep hill without your legs giving out. Nothing is free, you trade speed for ease. The takeaway, and I would check this landed, is that gearing does not add energy, it just repackages the effort you put in to match the terrain. The clarity-before-jargon habit is exactly how I would walk a client through a deal.$x$);
